Aug 22 2009 	Lots of good things...one big negative	It's tough for me to write this review because I really did like this hotel. So let me first say what I thought was good and then explain what the one big negative point was.The good stuff...The hotel's design: I live in mid-century modern home so I totally appreciated the design of this building and thought that they had done a very good job of making the hotel feel modern and up-to-date without compromising the integrity of the building. The furniture and decor in the lobby and the restaurants was very well done, inviting and comfortable.The room: Small but well designed so that I did not feel cramped. Plenty of storage. Very clean and cozy. It would have been nice to have an in-room coffee maker though. Room service coffee gets pricey and I'm not one to trudge downstairs just to get a free coffee upon first waking up. There is one very large window in the room so it gets decent natural light. More on the window below...The staff: Quick check in and check out. Room service was efficient. Staff members were courteous in the halls and elevators.The restaurants &amp; bar: The food was good and I felt that the service was good as well. Proximity: This was a business trip and the hotel was close to where I needed to be which is why I booked it.Ok, so with all this going for it, what is the one big negative? NOISE from the nightclub at the hotel.I checked in on a Saturday. I read the literature that was in the room and saw that I could request a &quot;window plug&quot; of some sort to block out the noise coming through the one very large window in the room. Since I had to get up early the next day, I thought that this would be a good idea. I called down to the desk and within seconds someone showed up with this giant circular pad that was covered in upholstery that he popped into the window frame.Now, it is important to note that there is a nightclub at the hotel on the lower level just above one of the restaurants. This nightclub apparently has some open roof areas and all rooms face this nightclub. I was on the 8th floor and when the club opened that night there was some considerable noise coming into my room from the nightclub below despite the giant window noise blocker thingy. I don't know what time the nightclub closed but it seemed that the noise went on until about 4 am or so. I managed to sleep but it was not a good night's sleep. I didn't bother to complain about it because it was a Saturday night and I was probably the only person in Manhattan that had to get up early the next day.The next 2 nights were ok and I slept fine. I guess the nightclub was not open.My last night in the hotel was awful. Apparently there was some sort of private party going on in the club below. Once again, I needed to get up early so I popped the noise blocker into the window and tried to settle in. There was a bad thunderstorm early in the night and it seemed that the club quieted down for an hour or so. Around 10:00, it seemed that the weather had cleared up and the party was back on...louder than ever. The music was so loud that there was no way that thing in the window was going to block it out. Especially the bass. It was like a non-stop thudding noise. After this had been going on for awhile, I called down to the front desk and asked how long this would be going on for. I was told until 1 am. I was also offered ear plugs. The person at the desk told me that he would move me but there were no open rooms. I really don't think moving me would have helped. The bass was thumping so loudly I am sure people heard it a few floors up as well. He also said that sometimes they can ask the DJ to turn down the music and they will comply. Huh? Did I book a room in a hotel or a nightclub?When I checked out the next morning, I was told that no one from management was in. So, I left my complaint with the person at the front desk. When you book a hotel room, there is a reasonable expectation that you will be able to get some sleep and that it will actually be quiet enough to sleep. This hotel is probably fine if you are going to be out until 2am and come back and crash. However, if you need to get to sleep or if sleep is something you expect to get at a hotel this may not be the best choice for you.	
