Jul 27 2005 	An oasis in NY	I recently checked into the Maritime Hotel in Chelsea, NY. The front desk staff was very friendly and accomodating. I had mistakenly booked my travel dates incorrectly, but they quickly remidied the situation and got me into one of their cozy rooms for the dates I needed. To be honest, they aren't huge, but the amenities, design and layout of the rooms totally makes up for the size. Thumbs up to the designers.The entire vibe of the hotel is so relaxed, a nice change from the typical stuffy high brow attitudes of other NY hotels. The restaurant in the hotel has an amazing courtyard. A perfect outdoor retreat in the middle of the NY! I was even able to check my email out there and get &quot;work&quot; accomplished thanks to the wireless internet. I will definitely return to The Maritime! Great staff, cute rooms, and wonderful food!	
Jul 8 2005	Great hotel horrible service	I stayed at the hotel for a weekend over July 4th. The rooms are excellent, and the building is beautiful. Great bathroom and really great touches. It has the potential to be an amazing place..... Almost perfect.....except for the people who work there.Only the staff let this place down. When I was at reception I asked for a duplicate copy of my receipt, and the clerk rolled his eyes. When I asked room service for my breakfast to be delayed one hour, the operator said &quot;well, it will be cold then&quot;. I had to carry my heavy bags up stairs, over the lobby, and to my room in full view of two sour-faced receptionists and one bell hop. The service in the courtyard cafe was at glacier speed, and some food came 20 minutes after others...it became a running joke between my friends and I about the service. Pay $300 a night in a hotel where people smile, it is much nicer for everyone.	
Jun 7 2005 	Pros and Cons	I come to NYC 8+ times a year on business and pleasure. For pure fun the location is great being just a block away from the Meatpacking District and Chelsea seems to get better all of the time. Lots of boutiques and places to eat and drink. The hotel itself is...well, different. The rooms are fine and everything works. The halls are very dark, the entrance is a bit odd. The staff is fine but not really on-the-ball. It took forever to get anything, from change for a $100 to checking my bags. As a business traveler, I want decent, quick food in the morning. The breakfast was slow, poor and tasted like it had been sitting in a warmer. (I tried it twice) If I had the time I would have gone to one of the dozen or so places nearby to eat, but I don't think I should have had to leave the hotel for basic eggs and toast. When I asked about the gym, I was told it was down the street and too the left. Well, on the west side a street is what, 200 yards long and then some? During the evening or on a warm weekend, the patio is jammed with a high energy crowd. Even at 2am on a Saturday night in June the place was packed! It's fun and you feel in the middle of the action. Best of all, no velvet ropes. So, if all you want is to be &quot;in the scene&quot;, stay at the Maritime. You'll probably enjoy it. If you want service and hospitality, try somewhere else.	
Mar 7 2005	Hip and Hospitable	We just returned from three great nights at the Maritime and I could not have been more pleased with the looks of the hotel and the wonderful hospitality. The nautical theme was prevelent throughout the hotel from the porthole windows to the tile in the bathroom. The rooms were typical New York boutique-small- however they were intelligently designed. They have a cruise ship theme where you can store all of your belongings. The beds were comfortable and the bathroom was clean and sleak. The rooms have a great stereo, flat screen tv, and the lights have dimmers to make the experience very un-hotel like. Also the staff couldn't be more accomodating and friendly. Everyone was pleasant displayed zero arrogance. If you stay there, check out the Chelsea Market across the street for a great wine shop, bakeries, etc. Granted I am not a freequent traveler to NYC but we could not have asked for a better hotel experience.	
Feb 24 2005	Great spot in Chelsea	I have stayed at The Maritime several times and have always had a good experience. Let's face it- NY is expensive, large hotels rooms are far and few between, and the big Apple is hardly known for great service.All that said, the Maritime is a teriffic place to stay in a neighborhood where there are not many good options. The room is indeed small, but beautifully designed and well appointed. Bed is amazingly confortable, and the bathroom is lovely. The large round window, although very cool, can be a bit drafty and noisy. The hotel will be happy to supply a &quot;Window Plug&quot; however - basically a large folding piece of foam wrapped in fabric- to block out sound and noise. It works perfectly. Lobby is nice and mellow (apart from weekends when it's mobbed with 20 somethings). Restaurant and bar are quite good, and there are plenty of others nearby. Pastis, Florent, etc.Service is ok. Yes all with an air of laid backness (or lazyness?), but I have never had a problem. All in all a great spot and cool architecture.My one small crtiticism is the lack of a ramp for one's luggage. It's a bit of a pain to lug a heavy suitcase up those front steps.	
Dec 4 2004	cautionary tale	I liked this hotel just fine and think the location is great for all heat-seeking out of towners. The room was small but that's to be expected. My main complaint is that the beds, while very comfortable, were made up with down pillows and a down comforter. I woke up from coughing fits both nights of my stay. I assumed I was coming down with a cold and did not realize until it was too late that I was allergic to the bed. So, if you have allergies, make sure they use hypoallergenic bedding.I have stayed in some of the finest and some of the worst hotels all over the world and do not recall ever having been allergic to a bed before.	
Jul 5 2004	hip hotel without the hospitality	This seems like a hotel that is trying to be a hip lounge and it does neither very well. The rooms are small, everything seems a bit dark, and the service is really not very good. You do pay big time hotel prices though. I would like to elaborate on the service aspect. I expect hospitality in a hotel. The hotel staff here just does not seem very professional or particularly helpful. They offer a very relaxed attitude but it is potentially too relaxed for the type of clientele they are attracting. On check-out, I unfortunately left an item in the room. I spoke to someone after I had departed and asked them to retrieve it for me. They found the item and promised to send it immediately. After waiting 3 weeks, I called them. The item was still sitting at the front desk unsent. No one knew what had happened. This is just an example of my entire experience with the staff. The high points were the shower, the port-hole window and the location.	
Jun 29 2004	Excellent Hotel	Excellent place to stay. You'll read all kinds of reviews on this site but the bottom line is that this is one of the best hotel experiences in New York.Great Location. Great service. Great People. Great Nightlife. Good sized rooms. Good bathrooms (great shower). All the amenities that you need. There are a few things that happened during our stay that are worth mentioning.1)Free computer access. Not sure if they had this on every floor, but our floor had a Windows based computer and MAC with a Laser printer that was available to guests at no charge.2)My wife likes to drink her own brand of tea and when we asked to have hot water sent up to the room every morning they did not charge us for it. Other hotels would charge you like they would for having tea delivered to your room, plus 18% gratuity, plus a $3 service charge. The Maritime did not charge us. A minor detail but it's nice to see a hotel that charges for things using common sense and doesn't try to nickel and dime you to death.3)Great scene at night. When we arrived at 6am in the morning off the red eye the place was so quiet.....but once 6pm rolled around you could not find a place to sit or stand. What a great way to start off your night...it's what you want in a hotel. Good place to have drinks and set the tone for the night, you can easily hang out at the hotel for the entire evening.	
May 29 2004	At First Confusion - Then Loved It!	I went to NYC this week on a business trip and found this great hotel right next to where I was working. At first, the hotel left me confused... sushi bar in the basement?, long steps to the lobby, wasn't clear where the front entrance was or where to park (across the street), and the lobby was dark and dim and surrounded by a restaurant, my room wasn't quite ready when expected, but the staff seemed overly friendly and eager to help. I checked in and went to work. After returning at night - the place came to life and was simply awesome. First, the rooms are great - they're on the small side, but everything you'd want in a first rate hotel is there - GREAT bed, one of the most comfortable I've spent the night in - attention to detail, fun, and &quot;no expense spared&quot; surround you. For business travlers - they have the much desired high speed wireless Internet access (worked great, breeze to set up and connect) and a cordless phone (why doesn't every hotel have one?) The mini-bar is well stocked with all sorts of goodies and treats beyond the basic alcohol and candy bars. Where else would you find tea bags for your eyes and saki? LCD television, game consoles, etc. - you won't be bored in a bland hotel room here. Now the downstairs... the hotel starts to come to life around 6:00pm, and the momentum builds all night. This is definitely one of the places to be in New York at night - the people and personalities are many and varied - as it is be expected in this part of town. But best of all, everyone is friendly and happy - you can start a conversation with anyone, or they will start one with you. The restaurant was the icing on the cake - service was absolutely superb, the staff was beyond friendly, and the food was fantastic - and all at a very reasonable price. You might expct to pay twice as much from the atmosphere alone. I spent all night at a table outside just enjoying the evening, the great food, and the people around me.Why would you want to avoid this hotel? If you want something completely quiet and sedate, if you need to have a large room to spread out in, if you expect a hotel to be bland and predictable, this is not the place for you. If you're looking for something very different and just plain fun, while also being reaonably priced, try the Maritime. You'll very likely be back, I know I won't hesitate to return here.	
Mar 26 2004	Overall a good hotel...	I travel to NYC everyweek and have tried several hotels in the past year. I've been dissapointed with the majority of them, whether it's because of service, room temperature, uncomfortable beds, cold showers, etc... I just stayed at The Maritime for the first time this week. Although it's not the most convenient location from my job, I have decided to stay here everyweek. Positives: friendly staff, fun and hip atmosphere, very clean, good bed and pillows, nice room amenities(tv/radio/dvd/alarm), large selection of restaurants in the neighborhood.Negatives: Small rooms, Small side entrance, location	
